##City's wildlife: Raccoon dogs are more abundant in the community than in the wild, and bats need not panic when it comes to wintering. | In depth

MICRO-SIGNAL BQSHENYIDU

Beijing Youth Daily reports from the official public number

Reporter / Wei Xiaohan

Editor / Edward Shek, Jianhua Song

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
A raccoon dog photographed by Wang Fang in Shanghai

An epidemic has brought wildlife back into view. Aside from "eating game" and "carrying viruses, " many people know little about the city's wildlife.

When these "neighbors" have no intention of visiting the human world, some people fear, panic, panic, put them naturally in the "opposite" . The new outbreak of pneumonia has many ordinary people thinking, "how do we get along with the animals in the city? "

Wang Fang was a city child who grew up in Beijing. In his memory, Beijing in the 1980s often seen timid squirrels and weasels, with the city's development, now "can only go looking for. ". The result is still beyond his expectation -- "the species and number of urban animals are far beyond the imagination of ordinary citizens, and they can maintain peaceful relations with human beings for a long time. ".

After a career at Peking University and the Smithsonian Institution and the Michigan State University, Wang worked for the Institute of Biodiversity Sciences at Fudan University. Based in Shanghai, he and his team have been working for the past year on a project called citizen scientists in the city, which recruits citizens to record the movements and conditions of the city's wildlife. Under the epidemic, they set up in parks, communities, forests, 80 infrared cameras day and night to record the life of wild animals track.

In Wang Fang's view, urban wildlife management is a complex issue, which not only means the protection of animals and the popularization of science, but also involves the problems of destruction and infectious diseases, but there is no doubt that the diversity of the wild life in Florida is of great significance to the ecological environment of a city.

This is the dictation given by the king.

Wang Fang told the volunteers about the project

Urban "shelters"

In downtown Beijing, I have seen many a wild weasel. Some in Guomao, Haidian District Huangzhuang, some in Jingshan Hill, Gulou East Street, Hepingli. In Qingpu District, Jinshan District, Fengxian District and Nanhui, you can see a raccoon in the wild -- a fat mountain animal, and you've probably heard the idiom for it, a raccoon of a feather.

If you zoom in, there's a lot of wildlife in the city. In Beijing, for example, there are weasels, hedgehogs, chipmunks and rock squirrels, and of course there are plenty of birds and insects. Add in the surrounding Miyun District, Mentougou District, Yanqing District and Changping District, and you have some very large animals, such as the roe deer, wild boar, leopard cat, and so on.

We might not imagine that some of the city's wildlife is so widespread and adaptable. If you ask me to draw a map of Beijing without weasels, it is difficult. They can usually be seen within two or three kilometers of the community. We do ecological research, and infrared cameras in Shanghai's parks may capture more wildlife than in the wild in the minshan mountains or the Qin Mountains mountains, only the ocelots have been replaced by hedgehogs and weasels.

These wildlife are relatively small and intelligent, and can quickly adjust their time to city life.

I've had some amazing times with them. One night a raccoon dog and I met in Qingpu District, Shanghai, and several times he sat at my feet, scratching himself in a daze. And at six or seven in the evening, in Beijing, where it is not yet completely dark, weasels will appear in the neighborhood with swagger. They seem very calm in the face of human beings. There are cars going around, and there are people walking and walking their dogs two or three meters away, you know, they're supposed to be very timid animals.

Compared to twenty or three years ago, my feeling is that there are fewer wild animals in the city and people are more calm. I grew up in Beijing. In the 1980s, there were rivers and springs all over Haidian District. There were mountains around Peking University. Back then, hedgehogs and squirrels were everywhere, remembered as timid and timid, and more often kept at arm's length. Even earlier, in the 1970s, there were wolves in Beijing's Xizhimen and Beitaipingzhuang, and jackals could be seen in the suburbs.

The environment of the city has changed a lot since then. There are no woods or fields when I was a child. The Barren hills have become supermarkets, communities and small squares. There must be fewer places where animals live, even less. But they've probably seen a lot of human activity, and know when to hide, and aren't as timid as they used to be. This observation is basically consistent with the international observation of urban animals.

Cities naturally attract wildlife, and their special properties provide protection for some wildlife. Raccoon dogs are now rare in the wild. They used to be found in Great Lesser Khingan, East China, central China, and Guizhou, but in the last 30 years they have become extinct, we suspect that there may have been an outbreak of a deadly disease in this population.

In Shanghai, we were surprised to find raccoon dogs in over 60 neighborhoods. The city is like a sanctuary, the wild world is turned upside down, and the raccoons in this "sanctuary" thrive. They've adapted to city life for over a decade, living near sewers and vents. It turns out that catching frogs, small fish and shrimps in the wild has turned into dumpster diving, eating cat food in the city, and even going around the dining halls and restaurants to see if you can pick up some leftovers.

So, raccoon dog became the origin of the wild animal we seek in the city.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On the 10th day of the first lunar month, the staff of the wildlife protection and management station in Minhang district, Shanghai, dispatched six times and received a report to drive away the over-wintering bats that residents saw around their homes (picture from the Internet) 

Conflict and coexistence

What happened to the wild raccoon? We're trying to find out why. There's no record of it. Raccoon dog is not a "protected animal" and used to be farmed to provide fur, so we can only find information on how to drug it, take antibiotics, and see a doctor. But how has the population changed in nature? Unfortunately, there's no record of that.

Before the outbreak, we took 100 citizen volunteers to set up infrared cameras in parks and communities in Shanghai to record the activities of wild animals, including raccoon dogs. Now, because of the epidemic, we can't recycle the equipment, and these 80 cameras are still working around the clock, some in places where people are more active, some in the forest, some near wetlands, we want to monitor an area that covers all types of urban environments.

We recruited these volunteers through the citizen scientists program, teachers, government workers, programmers, students, all kinds of people. There was a woman from the education bureau in Baoshan District who planned to take the data directly into the classroom, and a director of a documentary film about the city of Shanghai who wanted to document our research. It's like a living thing, growing on its own.

When we did a survey in a residential area in Shanghai, we found that most residents had a friendly attitude towards wildlife, but it was mixed with more and more complicated opinions. Sometimes a raccoon dog will turn over a human balcony, knock over a flowerpot, or dig a hole in the garden, and the residents will have a problem. Raccoon dog like centralized defecation, if it happened to pile in whose window, downstairs, there will be discontent.

Conflicts between wildlife and people are common in cities, especially in ecologically good places. When I was doing my postdoctoral research in the United States, I encountered large headed raccoons clawing open the sliding doors of the institute, their watery eyes searching for food and water. When Fed raccoons discover that people can provide them with food, they go into people's houses to steal things, chew up windows and even destroy houses. In the United States, raccoons can cause more than million in damage to homes each year, and they can cause fires, electricity leaks, and so on.

In the United States, it's not just raccoons. coyotes, possums, skunks and people are also at odds. Several of my colleagues'cars and people have been sprayed with skunks that smell so bad they can't be driven for two weeks and can blind people and their pets in the short term. In India, leopards go to cities to kill dogs and even hurt people, while in Europe, wild boar, squirrels and foxes also cause economic losses.

Another problem comes from infectious diseases carried by wild animals. There is a disease in the United States called lyme disease, which is transmitted by ticks. There are a lot of white-tailed deer around the city, and when ticks suck their blood and suck people's blood, they can pass on infectious diseases from wild animals to people, one of them was accompanied by a severe allergic reaction, which at one point required high doses of hormones to survive.

Gradually we found that, in fact, human and animal conflict is a very normal thing. As China's urban ecology gets better and more wildlife gathers in cities, it is likely that in 20 or 30 years, conflicts between animals and people in cities will become a problem, and it will be too late to investigate. Let's just accumulate the data now, maybe we can use it later.

Now, in the early days of the study, a large number of instruments and equipment are being recorded automatically in the city, and there is no way to retrieve the data because of the outbreak. Follow up with direct contact with the animal, such as putting a GPS collar on a raccoon dog to track its movements and see what kind of trouble it can run into in the city. Now, in light of the outbreak, there may be some panic, and we're conducting a no-contact investigation.

How long will the search for wildlife in this city last? Forever, I hope. Really, as long as we are in Shanghai, the work will not stop, because the urban environment is constantly changing, so this thing is not the end of the day.

Animal passage across the five rings (Effect Diagram)

Animal passage across the five rings

When we survey in Shanghai, some residents will worry about raccoon dog rabies? Is it possible for a Hedgehog to carry a bloodsucking tick? The possibility exists in theory, but as long as people don't touch it. People do not take the initiative to contact, feed wild animals, see after they do not have to drive or even poisoning.

In the long run, we can set up surveillance networks for urban wildlife diseases, and ideally, we might need to regularly sample wild animals to see if they carry infectious diseases. The network exists, but the investigation may not be sufficiently robust to provide sufficient reassurance.

In fact, from the point of view of the citizens, can do limited, the greater challenge to urban designers. If the city has some good design, such as the endless lawn around some shrubs, dwarf trees, people and animals directly "big eyes, small eyes" situation will not appear.

In Beijing, wildlife may head for the JINGMI aqueduct or the Kunyu river when it needs water, but the embankments are concrete and the animals can only concentrate in one or two places near the water. But like the Rhine or the Manhattan River, surrounded by natural embankments, lots of soft soil, lots of access to water, more options for animals and people to use these rivers and lakes, naturally separated.

Over the years, our cities have tried many things.

The most typical is Beijing's Olympic Forest Park. When it was first built, it was a big barren beach. Three years after it was built, more than 200 species of birds appeared in the park. The park is separated by the fifth ring road. What about the animals? They designed a special passage for wildlife, like an overpass, like a lid over the five rings.

When we first started designing it, you never know if an animal will use it. Soon after the construction, we found that hedgehogs and weasels would really use this passageway. Trees and bushes were planted around the passageway. When the animals found that they could walk, their heads went flat. They ran back and forth around the two sides of the fifth ring. This was a good try.

There are good examples of Olympic forest parks, and there are examples of destruction, both good and bad.

The biggest threat to animals in cities, for example, comes from the misuse of pesticides, herbicides and rodenticides. The rats and vermin may not be destroyed, or they may soon recover, but the hedgehogs, squirrels, and mantids of this place will never recover. As long as these poisons are around, it's hard to say that the city is a good place for animals to live.

Europeans in the evaluation of their own forests when there is a word, called Empty Forest (Empty Forest) , that although the Forest is well restored, but there are no animals, this Forest is no ecological function. Our urban ecological construction is certainly getting better and better, but in the process we need to prevent empty forests. Chemically treated green space. It's beautiful, but it doesn't work.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
A raccoon dog that Wang Fang met on the street in Shanghai

Wildlife and urban value

We will find some cities are very beautiful, Dali have Cangshan Erhai Lake, Hangzhou have West Lake, hills, overseas have Edinburgh, Washington, including Barcelona, people live very comfortable in the city. One reason is that nature and human activities are inlaid together. Just as we speak of the most beautiful places in Beijing, the Old Beijing has a saying of "eight scenes of Yanjing" . It must be a combination of place names and natural landscapes. For example, Jimen tobacco trees have trees, Jintai sunset has mountains and the setting sun. This is an idealized picture of the city.

In many foreign cities, the natural skeleton remains untouched. New York, for example, maintains a central park in the heart of a densely populated and high-rise city, where wild animals such as squirrels are readily available. From the first day the city was built, it was decided that the wilderness was to stay.

There are many densely populated areas in China's cities. There is no place with low population density around the fifth ring road of Beijing. When we built the city, we filled in many natural (areas) , such as Beijing's Beitaipingzhuang, there used to be more than a dozen rivers, now a small river. The old river network was filled in during the renovation of the Old City, but it will be a little difficult to find back, and may need to be replaced in some way. Since there are no big ones, we can build small ecosystems, and connect them to each other for big functions.

Are The wild animals living well in the city? I can only answer -- Harvard is no. They face a variety of threats, from chemicals, or simple vegetation, their lack of shelter and food, or the city's stray cats and dogs to the threat of wildlife and so on. So that's why we've been talking to the landscaping department, about planting trees and shrubs, about planting a thriving indigenous species, about making the urban green space not ornamental, but useful.

During this particular phase of the epidemic, urban wildlife such as bats can go through a difficult time. (Note: According to media reports, during the outbreak, there were many incidents of residents in Shanghai finding wintering bats near their homes, which caused panic; at the same time, legal experts suggested that ecological extermination of animals that are prone to public health problems would be allowed, causing controversy.) In the future, more and more cities may try to drive them away, or avoid them altogether, we want to move towards the latter, so we've been talking to city authorities to persuade citizens to reduce unnecessary panic.

If a bat or other wild animal enters a resident's home by mistake, it can be handled by the local animal protection agency to disinfect the place where the wild animal has stayed without killing it.

Why is wildlife important to cities when it can cause problems and city management problems?

This is the last question that any of us in ecology would want to answer, and it's unavoidable. If you really count the value of wild animals, you can probably tell some, such as urban bats can control the number of flies, mosquitoes, grassland pests can be given to hedgehogs, weasels can reduce the number of rats.

But more importantly, wildlife is an expression of urban values. Cities naturally attract wild animals, as long as we build a beautiful city, there are running water, hills, there is a strong natural vegetation, wild animals will be more. Conversely, the absence of wildlife means that the city itself is badly built. Wildlife Diversity is the result of an urban development.
